<br>
I get there, clear out the annoying green prisoners with my air pet armed with two gnoll hide lariats (was 28 at the time). I med up, and then start in on Osargen. I damage shield the pet, and send him in to do his work. To my surprise, Osargen ran directly at ME. I say no sweat, i let the pet stun, thinking that'll be a nice taunt. but stun wears off, and Osargen runs at me again. Long story short, the pet taunt did virtually nothing, and i died. <br>
<br>
I went back with an earth pet and he was easy as cake. Has anyone else encountered any mobs like this? Would be nice to know ahead of time. <p>Adelphi Etrigan
Conjurer and scholar of the Spurned.
Lanys T.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/useek9.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Seek 9</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 82<br> <font color=#333333>(11/6/00 2:36:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=92.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   It is the Range</span><hr size=1> <br>
Were you in a confined place?  It sounds like it.<br>
<br>
This is how it works. . . <br>
<br>
If you are soloing vs a mob that has some brains (not undead, or animal), you will need some good range to get your pet to keep it off you.  Try this:  go to Unrest with your Air elemental.  You will not have any problem getting most undead mobs to stick to it, even in a small room.  Now, take you air elemental and go to Splitpaw or Aviks.  If you are not standing waaayyy back, the gnoll or birdie is going to keep inching towards you all the time and you will have to continue backing up to relock the creature on your pet.<br>
<br>
Thus, the usefulness of Earth.  For soloing in a cramped place, against thinking &quot;smart&quot; creatures, the lock-down root effect is what you need.<br>
<br>
The Air pet &quot;super taunt&quot; will often work because it gives you time to get to a good range away from the mob.  Again, this is often only easy to do while outdoors.<br>
<br>
If you have a &quot;real&quot; tank, this is uneccessary.<br>
<br>
Lastly, so you you want to use Air, Water, Fire, while soloing &quot;smart&quot; mobs in dungeons?  Well, if you are willing to take some hits, you can do this.  Single pull, and every time the critter starts to hit you, run right over your pet's position, getting the mob on the opposite side of pet again.   The nuke, heal, whatever.  The mob WILL come off the pet in a little while and whack you again, so just repeat the manuveur. <p><b>Seek Pyremaker</b><br>
Mage 35th Season, Xegony</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzorryn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zorryn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#333333>(11/6/00 3:24:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=92.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mobs that totally ignore pets</span><hr size=1> I had the same problem with Osargen.  However, I was trying to solo him at lvl23 so even my Earth pet was inadequate.  His root did not stick often enough.  I usually ended the battles with little HPs and 50mana.  This combined with having to continually clean the green prisoners made this solo camp not worth it to me.  At that point, I decided to give the skulking brutes near Dalnir a shot and I was glad I did. I made 29 on those brutes.<br>
